threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factors were that it matches yara rules with files that have detections and it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.32, stripped

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature fires on the presence of Base64 encoded URI prefixes (http:// and https://) across any file. The simple presence of such strings is not inherently an indicator of malicious content, but is worth further investigation.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a ransomware variant, likely 'INC Ransom', designed to target Linux systems, specifically VMWare ESXi environments. It accepts command-line arguments to control its behavior, such as targeting specific files or directories ('--file', '--dir'), and an '--esxi' flag to trigger VM-specific attacks. When targeting ESXi, it executes shell commands to list all VMs, delete their snapshots ('vim-cmd vmsvc/snapshot.removeall'), and forcefully stop them ('esxcli vm process kill', 'vim-cmd vmsvc/power.off'). The malware then recursively traverses directories, encrypting files using a thread pool for speed. It renames encrypted files and drops ransom notes in `.txt` and `.html` formats. A base64-decoded string reveals a URL pointing to a Twitter hashtag for 'incransom', confirming its identity.
